<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="56" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,463]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,260,284]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Etymology.</emphasis>
I take pleasure in naming this species in honor of friend, colleague, and fellow coleopterist, Maxwell V. L. Barclay. He has been a most congenial and helpful contact in “the beetle room” at The Natural History Museum, London.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="56" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,463]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,367,392]" pageId="3" pageNumber="56">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The shining dorsal surface with strongly reduced vestiture, black, sparsely setose pronotum, coarsely rugose-reticulate, bluish-purple elytra, and strongly reduced humeral carinae are diagnostic for this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
